{"title_page": "In the Dark (American TV series)", "text_new": "{{Distinguish|Into the Dark (TV series)}}\n{{short description|American TV series}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = In the Dark\n| image                    = In the Dark (U.S. TV series) Title Card.jpg\n| caption                  = \n| genre                    = [[Comedy-drama]]\n| based_on                 = \n| creator                  = Corinne Kingsbury\n| developer                = \n| starring                 = {{Plainlist|<!-- Organized by broadcast credit order, with new main cast added to the end of the list -->\n* Perry Mattfeld\n* [[Rich Sommer]]\n* Brooke Markham\n* [[Casey Deidrick]]\n* Keston John\n* Morgan Krantz\n* Thamela Mpumlwana \n* Derek Webster\n* [[Kathleen York]]\n}}\n| composer                 = {{Plainlist|\n* Will Blair\n* Brooke Blair\n* Will Bates\n}}\n| country                  = United States\n| language                 = English\n| num_seasons              = 2<!-- Or num_series. Increment when new seasons/series begin. See template documentation for more info. -->\n| num_episodes             = 14<!-- Value is incremented when new episodes air. See template documentation for more info. -->\n| list_episodes            = #Episodes\n| executive_producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Ben Stiller]] \n* Corinne Kingsbury\n* Jackie Cohn\n* [[Michael Showalter]]\n* Nicky Weinstock\n* John Weber\n* Frank Siracusa\n* Andrea Raffaghello\n}}\n| location                 = \n| cinematography           = {{Plainlist|\n* Brian Burgoyne\n* Bradford Lipson\n* Onno Weeda\n}}\n| editor                   = {{Plainlist|\n* Jessica Brunetto\n* Tod Modisett\n* Gregory Cusumano\n* Warren Bowman\n* Bari Winter\n* Josiah Ruis\n}}\n| camera                   = [[Single-camera setup|Single-camera]]\n| runtime                  = 42 minutes\n| company                  = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Red Hour Films]]\n* [[Warner Bros. Television]]\n* [[CBS Television Studios]]\n}}\n| distributor              = [[CBS Television Distribution]]\n| network                  = [[The CW]]\n| picture_format           = [[1080i]] ([[High-definition television|HDTV]])\n| audio_format             = [[Dolby Digital]] with [[Descriptive Video Service]] on [[second audio program|SAP]] \n| first_aired              = {{Start date|2019|4|4}}\n| last_aired               = {{End date|present}}\n| preceded_by              = \n| followed_by              = \n| related                  =\n| website                  = https://www.cwtv.com/shows/in-the-dark/\n| website_title            = Official website\n| production_website       = \n}}\n'''''In the Dark''''' is an American [[comedy-drama]] television series, created by Corinne Kingsbury for [[The CW]], which debuted as a mid-season entry during the [[2018\u201319 United States network television schedule|2018\u201319 television season]]. On January 30, 2018, [[The CW]] ordered the show to pilot, with [[Michael Showalter]] set to direct. In May 2018, the show received a series order. The series premiered on April 4, 2019. In April 2019, the series was renewed for a second season that premiered on April 16, 2020. In January 2020, The CW renewed the series for a third season.<!--Per WP:CITELEAD, references are not needed in the lead if it is sourced in the body of the article!-->\n\n==Premise==\nAn irreverent blind woman in her twenties, Murphy drifts through life in a drunken haze. She has only two friends\u2014Jess, her understanding roommate, and Tyson, a teenage drug-dealer who saved her from a violent mugging. Out for a walk with her guide dog, Pretzel, she stumbles upon a corpse that must be Tyson's, but it disappears before the police arrive. When they do not seem inclined to investigate, Murphy clings onto the only thing that can keep her together: figuring out what happened to her friend.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.tv.nu/program/in-the-dark-2018 |title=In the Dark |publisher=tv.nu |language=sv, en |accessdate=January 22, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190122144953/https://www.tv.nu/program/in-the-dark-2018 |archive-date=January 22, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> She resolves to solve the murder herself, while also managing her colorful dating life and the job she hates at \"Guiding Hope\", a school for training guide dogs run by her parents.\n\n==Cast and characters==\n<!--[[MOS:TVCAST]] > \"cast listing [is] ordered according to the original broadcast credits, with new cast members...added to the end of the list\".-->\n\n===Main===\n* Perry Mattfeld as Murphy Mason, a young woman whose blindness, introverted personality, and self-destructive lifestyle make her unwelcoming to most people. When a friend is murdered, she finds a new purpose in trying to find his killer.\n* [[Rich Sommer]] as Dean Riley, a cop who sympathizes with Murphy since his daughter is also blind.\n* Brooke Markham as Jess Damon, a veterinarian at Guiding Hope and Murphy's roommate and best friend. She also assists Murphy as an informal aide at times.\n* [[Casey Deidrick]] as Max Parish, a food truck owner and associate of Darnell who becomes attracted to Murphy.\n* Keston John as Darnell Parker, a local gang leader and Tyson's cousin, who Murphy turns to for help finding him.\n* Morgan Krantz as Felix Bell, Murphy's colleague at Guiding Hope. He later buys the school when it goes bankrupt.\n* Thamela Mpumlwana as Tyson Parker, a teenager who saved Murphy from a violent mugging and became her closest friend until his untimely death.\n* Derek Webster as Hank Mason, Murphy's adoptive father and the owner of Guiding Hope until he sells it to Felix.\n* [[Kathleen York]] as Joy Mason, Murphy's adoptive mother. Unlike Hank, she is less accepting of Murphy's poor life choices.\n\n===Recurring===\n* Humberly Gonzalez as Vanessa, Jess's girlfriend.\n* Calle Walton as Chloe, Dean's daughter who is also blind and looks up to Murphy as a big sister.\n* [[Saycon Sengbloh]] as Jules Becker, Dean's partner and Darnell's love interest.\n* [[Lindsey Broad]] as Chelsea, Murphy's bartender friend and Dean's love interest.\n* [[Ana Ayora]] as Det. Sarah Barnes, Max's confidential handler  \n* Pretzel, Murphy's loyal seeing-eye dog, is played by Levi.\n* [[Matt Murray (actor)|Matt Murray]] as Gene (season 2)<ref name=\"MattM\"/>\n* [[Nicki Micheaux]] as Nia Bailey.\n*[[Natalie Liconti]] as Sterling.\n\n===Criticisms over lack of disabled actors===\n\nThe show received some criticism of the casting of a sighted actor playing a blind character. British actor James Moore, who plays [[List_of_Emmerdale_characters_(2018)#Ryan_Stocks|a disabled character]] in the [[soap opera]] ''[[Emmerdale]]'' and has [[ cerebral palsy |a disability]] himself, argued that disabled actors will always be better placed to play disabled roles due to their life experience.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://unitemagazine.co.uk/emmerdale-actor-calls-out-cripping-up-in-new-us-drama/|title=Emmerdale actor calls out cripping up in new US drama|last=Campbell|first=Katie|date=20 March 2019|work=Unite Magazine|accessdate=15 October 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191015145210/https://unitemagazine.co.uk/emmerdale-actor-calls-out-cripping-up-in-new-us-drama/|archive-date=October 15, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> On [[review aggregator]] [[Rotten Tomatoes]], critics worried that the \"questionable treatment of physical handicaps may leave some viewers with a dim impression.\"<ref name=\"Rotten Tomatoes\">{{cite web |title=In the Dark: Season 1 |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/in_the_dark_2019/s01 |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |publisher=[[Fandango Media]] |date=2019 |accessdate=April 12, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190407041429/https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/in_the_dark_2019/s01 |archive-date=April 7, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nDuring a panel discussion at the [[Television Critics Association]] press tour, executive producer Nicky Weinstock defended the choices, claiming that they initially auditioned blind actors, but ultimately cast Perry because she was the best actor for the role.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thewrap.com/in-the-dark-producers-explain-why-they-didnt-cast-a-blind-actress-in-the-lead-role/|title=\u2018In the Dark\u2019 Producers Explain Why They Didn\u2019t Cast a Blind Actress in the Lead Role|last=Baysinger|first=Tim|date=31 January 2019|work=Unite Magazine|accessdate=15 October 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191015145207/https://www.thewrap.com/in-the-dark-producers-explain-why-they-didnt-cast-a-blind-actress-in-the-lead-role/|archive-date=October 15, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Production==\n[[File:In the Dark filming Toronto 01.jpg|thumb|left|Filming for ''In the Dark'' in [[Toronto]], Ontario, Canada.]]\n\n===Development===\nThe series was created by Corinne Kingsbury for [[The CW]], to debut during the [[2018\u201319 United States network television schedule|2018\u201319 television season]].<ref name=\"PilotOrder\">{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2018/01/roswell-reboot-p-greg-berlanti-rob-thomas-6-cw-pilot-orders-record-total-of-9-pilots-1202274800/|title='Roswell' Reboot, Projects Produced By Greg Berlanti & Rob Thomas Among 6 CW Pilot Orders For Record Total Of 9 Pilots|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=January 30, 2018|accessdate=April 2, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180403112355/https://deadline.com/2018/01/roswell-reboot-p-greg-berlanti-rob-thomas-6-cw-pilot-orders-record-total-of-9-pilots-1202274800/|archive-date=April 3, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Showalter\">{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2018/02/the-big-sick-michael-showalter-direct-the-cw-pilot-in-the-dark-1202290872/|title='The Big Sick' Helmer Michael Showalter Set To Direct the CW Pilot 'In the Dark'|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=February 15, 2018|accessdate=April 2, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180323173745/http://deadline.com/2018/02/the-big-sick-michael-showalter-direct-the-cw-pilot-in-the-dark-1202290872/|archive-date=March 23, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> On January 30, 2018, The CW officially ordered the [[Television pilot|pilot]].<ref name=\"PilotProducers\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/roswell-reboot-six-cw-pilot-pickups-1080380|title='Roswell' Reboot Among Six CW Pilot Pickups|last=Goldberg|first=Lesley|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=January 30, 2018|accessdate=March 5, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180305001850/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/roswell-reboot-six-cw-pilot-pickups-1080380|archive-date=March 5, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The series was [[greenlit]] on May 11, 2018.<ref name=\"SeriesOrder\">{{cite web|last=Petski|first=Denise|url=http://deadline.com/2018/05/the-cw-picks-up-charmed-roswell-reboots-tvd-originals-offshoot-ilegacies-n-the-dark-greg-berlanti-pilot-to-series-1202388840/|title=The CW Picks Up 'Charmed' & 'Roswell' Reboots, 'TVD'/'Originals Offshoot, 'In The Dark' & Greg Berlanti Pilot To Series|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=May 11, 2018|accessdate=May 11, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180516060159/http://deadline.com/2018/05/the-cw-picks-up-charmed-roswell-reboots-tvd-originals-offshoot-ilegacies-n-the-dark-greg-berlanti-pilot-to-series-1202388840/|archive-date=May 16, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n''In the Dark'' is the first CW primetime series to carry [[Descriptive Video Service]] audio, though The CW, as a minor network, is not required to have any DVS provisions under the regulations for [[audio description]] for their affiliates, so the base of stations carrying that track is smaller than other networks where carriage of descriptive video is required. On January 10, 2019, The CW announced the premiere of the series on April 4 at 9 p.m.<ref name=\"premieredate\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/01/the-cw-spring-premiere-dates-jane-the-virgin-izombie-final-seasons-dcs-legends-of-tomorrow-arrow-1202532950/|title=The CW Sets Spring Premiere Dates: 'Jane The Virgin' & 'iZombie' Final Seasons, 'Legends Of Tomorrow' & 'The 100' Return|last1=Andreeva|first1=Nellie|last2=Dent|first2=Mark|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=January 10, 2019|accessdate=January 10, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190110214804/https://deadline.com/2019/01/the-cw-spring-premiere-dates-jane-the-virgin-izombie-final-seasons-dcs-legends-of-tomorrow-arrow-1202532950/|archive-date=January 10, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> On April 24, 2019, The CW renewed the series for a second season,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/the-cw-renews-all-american-in-the-dark-roswell-new-mexico-the-100-1203196720/|title=The CW Renews 'All American,' 'The 100,' 'In The Dark' and 'Roswell, New Mexico'|last=Thorne|first=Will|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=April 24, 2019|accessdate=April 24, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190425140813/https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/the-cw-renews-all-american-in-the-dark-roswell-new-mexico-the-100-1203196720/|archive-date=April 25, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> that is originally premiere on May 28, 2020,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/03/the-cw-sets-premiere-dates-stargirl-in-the-dark-season-2-final-season-the-100-1202874370/|title=The CW Sets Premiere Dates For 'Stargirl', 'In The Dark' Season 2 & Final Season Of 'The 100'|work=Deadline Hollywood|first=Denise|last=Petski|date=March 4, 2020|accessdate=March 4, 2020}}</ref> however it was moved to premiere date on April 16, 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/03/the-cw-in-the-dark-dc-stargirl-new-premiere-dates-whose-line-is-it-anyway-covid-19-scheduling-changes-supernatural-legacies-exit-final-season-coronavirus-1202893520/|title=The CW Shifts \u2018In the Dark\u2019 & \u2018Stargirl\u2019 Premiere Dates, Summons \u2018Whose Line\u2019 In COVID 19-Related Scheduling Changes As \u2018Supernatural\u2019 & \u2018Legacies\u2019 Bow Out|website=Deadline Hollywood|first=Nellie|last=Andreeva|date=March 26, 2020|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref> On January 7, 2020, the series was renewed for a third season.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://tvline.com/2020/01/07/the-cw-renewed-shows-2020-list-riverdale-flash/ |title=CW Renews Riverdale, Batwoman, Roswell, Black Lightning Plus 9 Others |last=Ausiello |first=Michael |work=TVLine |date=January 7, 2020 |accessdate=January 7, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200108032431/https://tvline.com/2020/01/07/the-cw-renewed-shows-2020-list-riverdale-flash/ |archive-date=January 8, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Casting===\nOn March 2, 2018, it was announced that Perry Mattfeld had been cast in the [[protagonist]] role of Murphy in the series' pilot, along with Brooke Markham as Jess, Murphy's roommate and best friend, and Keston John as Darnell, a local drug dealer;<ref name=\"Mattfeld\">{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2018/03/in-the-dark-perry-mattfeld-lead-the-cw-drama-pilot-brooke-markham-keston-john-cast-1202307097/|title='In The Dark': Perry Mattfeld To Topline the CW Drama Pilot; Brooke Markham & Keston John Co-Star|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=March 2, 2018|accessdate=April 2, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180402151145/https://deadline.com/2018/03/in-the-dark-perry-mattfeld-lead-the-cw-drama-pilot-brooke-markham-keston-john-cast-1202307097/|archive-date=April 2, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> followed on March 9 with Kathleen York as Joy, Murphy's mother, and Derek Webster as Hank, Joy's husband.<ref name=York>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2018/03/in-the-dark-kathleen-york-derek-webster-cast-the-cw-drama-pilot-1202325662/|title='In The Dark': Kathleen York & Derek Webster Cast In the CW Drama Pilot|last=Petski|first=Denise|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=March 9, 2018|accessdate=April 2, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180401031945/https://deadline.com/2018/03/in-the-dark-kathleen-york-derek-webster-cast-the-cw-drama-pilot-1202325662/|archive-date=April 1, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Austin Nichols]] was cast as Dean, a cop with a blind daughter, on March 12.<ref name=\"Nichols\">{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2018/03/in-the-dark-austin-nichols-star-the-cw-drama-pilot-1202336340/|title='In The Dark': Austin Nichols To Star In the CW Drama Pilot|last=Petski|first=Denise|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=March 12, 2018|accessdate=April 2, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180401171414/https://deadline.com/2018/03/in-the-dark-austin-nichols-star-the-cw-drama-pilot-1202336340/|archive-date=April 1, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> On May 16, 2018, The CW announced that the role of Dean had been recast;<ref name=\"NicholsDepart\">{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2018/05/in-the-dark-austin-nichols-recast-new-cw-series-1202392844/|title='In the Dark' New CW Series Recasts Role|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=May 16, 2018|accessdate=May 17, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180517063610/http://deadline.com/2018/05/in-the-dark-austin-nichols-recast-new-cw-series-1202392844/|archive-date=May 17, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> with Nichols thereafter replaced by Rich Sommer on July 13, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/07/in-the-dark-rich-sommer-cast-the-cw-drama-series-recasting-1202426130/|title='In the Dark': Rich Sommer To Co-Star On The CW Drama Series In Recasting|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=July 13, 2018|accessdate=July 16, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180715074153/https://deadline.com/2018/07/in-the-dark-rich-sommer-cast-the-cw-drama-series-recasting-1202426130/|archive-date=July 15, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> On September 10, 2019, [[Matt Murray (actor)|Matt Murray]] was cast in a recurring role for the second season.<ref name=\"MattM\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/09/all-rise-casts-mitch-silpa-matt-murray-in-the-dark-1202730524/|title='All Rise' Casts Mitch Silpa; Matt Murray Joins 'In The Dark'|work=Deadline Hollywood|first=Denise|last=Petski|date=September 10, 2019|accessdate=September 10, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190911194209/https://deadline.com/2019/09/all-rise-casts-mitch-silpa-matt-murray-in-the-dark-1202730524/|archive-date=September 11, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\n[[Filming]] on the pilot began on March 12, 2018,<ref name=Filming>{{cite web|url=https://www.actratoronto.com/whats-shooting/|title=What's Shooting?|publisher=ACTRA Toronto|accessdate=April 2, 2018|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/718uaP0LL?url=https://www.actratoronto.com/whats-shooting/|archive-date=July 24, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> in [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], Canada;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2018/03/tv-pilot-locations-2018-new-york-los-angeles-rankings-1202311512/|title=Pilot Locations 2018: New York Business Booming, Chicago Gains As Atlanta Slips|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=March 9, 2018|accessdate=April 2, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180506032758/http://deadline.com/2018/03/tv-pilot-locations-2018-new-york-los-angeles-rankings-1202311512/|archive-date=May 6, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[Wrap (filmmaking)|wrapped]] on March 28.<ref name=Filming /> [[Principal photography]] on season 1 began on August 8, 2018, and ended on December 21, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|title=What's Shooting|url=https://www.actratoronto.com/whats-shooting/|website=[[ACTRA|ACTRA Toronto]]|date=2017-2018|accessdate=19 April 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180922205319/https://www.actratoronto.com/whats-shooting/|archivedate=September 22, 2018}}</ref> Principal photography for the second season began on August 19, 2019 and expected to end January 24, 2020 in [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], [[Canada]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Current Productions {{!}} IATSE 873 |url=https://www.iatse873.com/current_productions |website=IATSE 873 |accessdate=November 1, 2019 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191101160158/https://www.iatse873.com/current_productions|archivedate=November 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Episodes==\n{{Series overview\n| color1     = #006161\n| link1      = #Season 1 (2019)\n| episodes1  = 13\n| start1     = {{Start date|2019|4|4}}\n| end1       = {{End date|2019|6|27}}\n\n| color2     = #AE8BAE\n| link2      = #Season 2 (2020)\n| episodes2  = \n| start2     = {{Start date|2020|4|16}}\n| end2       = \n}}\n\n===Season 1 (2019)===\n{{Episode table|background=#006161|overall=5|title=25|director=15|writer=25|airdate=12|viewers=10|country=U.S.|episodes=\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 1\n |Title           = Pilot\n |DirectedBy      = [[Michael Showalter]]\n |WrittenBy       = Corinne Kingsbury\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|4|4}}\n |Viewers         = 0.87<ref name=\"1.01\">{{cite web|url=https://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/daily-ratings/thursday-final-ratings-april-4-2019/|title='The Big Bang Theory,' 'Young Sheldon' adjust up, 'For the People' adjusts down: Thursday final ratings|last=Rejent|first=Joseph|work=TV by the Numbers|date=April 5, 2019|accessdate=April 5, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190405213929/https://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/daily-ratings/thursday-final-ratings-april-4-2019/|archive-date=April 5, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n |ShortSummary    = Murphy, a twenty-something antisocial blind woman, lives a relatively uneventful life full of drunken hookups and chain-smoking, with only Tyson, a teenage drug dealer who befriends her, to confide in. One night, while walking her dog, Murphy stumbles across what she believes to be Tyson's corpse, but when a police investigation turns up nothing, she spirals into depression, culminating in her getting caught cheating with a married man, Bryant, and losing her cane. When she returns to Tyson's old corner, she meets Darnell, Tyson's cousin and supplier, who tells her he's still alive. Bryant's wife, Gayle, rescinds a donation she made to Murphy's parents, driving a wedge between her and her mother Joy, who has given up trying to help her. Out of guilt, Murphy agrees to take a receptionist's job in her family's seeing dog school until she can pay them back. Incensed that no one believes her about Tyson, Murphy takes it upon herself to find him and has his phone's GPS tracked so she can find it. She notifies both Darnell and a friendly cop, Dean, but both discourage her from further investigation. Murphy's roommate Jess tells her that she knows Murphy will try to solve the case anyway.\n |LineColor       = 006161\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 2\n |Title           = Mommy Issues\n |DirectedBy      = [[Brian Dannelly]]\n |WrittenBy       = Amy Turner\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|4|11}}\n |Viewers         = 0.72<ref name=\"1.02\">{{cite web|url=https://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/daily-ratings/thursday-final-ratings-april-11-2019/|title='Gotham' repeat adjusts down: Thursday final ratings|last=Rejent|first=Joseph|work=TV by the Numbers|date=April 12, 2019|accessdate=April 12, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190412213453/https://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/daily-ratings/thursday-final-ratings-april-11-2019/|archive-date=April 12, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n |ShortSummary    = Murphy, unable to file a missing persons report for Tyson, decides to contact his mother Rhonda since she can do so. She also learns that, due to unpaid bills, her doctor is unwilling to treat her urinary infection. While visiting Dean for an update on the phone, Murphy tells Chloe that her father should consider dating. Jess becomes concerned that Vanessa doesn't love her. Joy and Hank organize a \"barkery\" event to raise money for the school, which Joy expects her daughter to attend. Murphy goes to Darnell for the address, but he refuses to tell her. Instead, she goes on a one-hour date with Max, one of his associates, for the information. Chloe sets her father up with Jade, a hooker from the station. Jess buys a sex toy to improve her relationship with Vanessa. Max takes Murphy to a beach, and then gives her the address. Murphy goes there, visits Tyson's room, and then tells Rhonda the truth. Dean contacts Murphy, and delivers the news that while Tyson's phone was completely wiped, they can now push forward with his case. Max shows up and gets her to agree to have a drink with him. Jess finds a new clue for Murphy. Darnell tells his incarcerated boss, Nia, that he'll deal with Murphy.\n |LineColor       = 006161\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 3\n |Title           = The Big Break\n |DirectedBy      = [[Norman Buckley]]\n |WrittenBy       = Lindsay Golder\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|4|18}}\n |Viewers         = 0.64<ref name=\"1.03\">{{cite web|url=https://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/daily-ratings/thursday-final-ratings-april-18-2019/|title='Grey's Anatomy,' 'The Big Bang Theory' adjust up, 'Supernatural' adjusts down: Thursday final ratings|last=Rejent|first=Joseph|work=TV by the Numbers|date=April 19, 2019|accessdate=April 19, 2019}}</ref>\n |ShortSummary    = While having sex, Murphy shoves Max off when he admits his feelings for her and injures his genitals. She and Jess go to speak with Tyson's girlfriend, but get kicked off school property. Murphy subsequently convinces Felix to hold an outreach event at the school so she can get access. Max tries to break through Murphy's emotional walls, so she kicks him out. Darnell steals some of the money he's collecting for Tyson's mother, but she refuses to take it. Felix is nervous about addressing the students, but finds that he can connect with them when he pretends to be blind. Murphy finds Keira's friends and learn that she's been missing school. She then has sex with a teacher, which accidentally exposes Felix's deceptio